About the project¶

In this notebook, we will be exploring the data of Breast Cancer (breast cancer wisconsin) and perform Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) on it. moreover we will be performing some Machine Learning (ML) on the data.

Our problem is classifiecation problem where we are trying to predict whether a patient has cancer or not.¶

Classification problem is a problem where we are trying to predict the class of an object, were not trying to predict a number (like age, height, price, etc.), We are trying to predict a class (dog or cat, men or women, ect) The data is collected from the Wisconsin Breast Cancer (WBC) Hospital, I imported the data from Kaggle, but it can also be downloaded from the UCI Machine Learning Repository. The data well be working on has 569 rows and 32 columns, meaning that there are 569 patients and 32 features. Our features are:

  1. ID number of the patient
  2. diagnosis (B = benign, M = malignant) - this is the class we are trying to predict
  3. radius (mean of distances from center to points on the perimeter)
  4. texture mean (mean of gray-scale values)
  5. perimeter (mean of perimeter)
  6. area (mean of area)
  7. smoothness (mean of perimeter minus area)
  8. compactness (perimeter^2 divided by area - 1.0)
  9. concavity (severity of concave portions of the contour)
  10. concave points (number of concave portions of the contour)
  11. symmetry (number of symmetry measurements used)
  12. fractal dimension - dimension of the fractal features of the object
  13. radius se (standard error of the mean of the radius)
  14. texture se (standard error of the mean of the texture)
  15. perimeter se (standard error of the mean of the perimeter)
  16. area se (standard error of the mean of the area)
  17. smoothness se (standard error of the mean of the smoothness)
  18. compactness se (standard error of the mean of the compactness)
  19. concavity se (standard error of the mean of the concavity)
  20. concave points se (standard error of the mean of the concave points)
  21. symmetry se (standard error of the mean of the symmetry)
  22. fractal dimension se (standard error of the mean of the fractal dimension)
  23. radiusworst (worst radius)
  24. textureworst (worst texture mean)
  25. perimeterworst (worst perimeter)
  26. areaworst (worst area)
  27. smoothnessworst (worst smoothness)
  28. compactnessworst (worst compactness)
  29. concavityworst (worst concavity)
  30. concave pointsworst (worst concave points)
  31. symmetryworst (worst symmetry)
  32. fractal dimensionworst (worst fractal dimension)

Main Libraries we will be using¶

In this notebook, we are going to use with several libraries and ML algorithms to predict whether a patient has cancer or not. Few libraries we are using are:

  1. pandas - a dataframe library, used to import and export data and store it in a dataframe
  2. numpy - a numerical library, used to perform mathematical operations on the data, and to perform matrix operations on the data
  3. seaborn - a visualization library, used to plot the data and to visualize the data
  4. matplotlib - a plotting and visualization library, used to plot the data and to visualize the data
  5. sklearn - a library that contains a lot of ML algorithms, used to train the model and to predict the model, it also contains a lot of metrics and functions to evaluate the model In the sklearn library, we have many functions and classes that we uses, such as: GridSearchCV, train_test_split, StandardScaler, LogisticRegression, confusion_matrix, accuracy_score, KNeighborsClassifier, ConfusionMatrixDisplay. In the last part of this notebook, we will be using Keras library and tensoflow library in order to implement deep learning algorithms such as Neural Network.
  6. Keras - a deep learning library, used to implement neural networks
  7. tensorflow - a deep learning library, used to implement neural networks

One hot encoding¶

In this section i want to explain why i've decided not to use one hot encoding.

One hot encoding¶

one hot encoding technique is used to convert categorical data to numerical data by creating a new column for each category and assigning 1 or 0 to each column.¶

because we have only 2 classes, we don't need to use one-hot encoding technique, we can simply use the following code.

if will decide to use one-hot encoding technique, we will have 2 new columns in our dataframe and becuse of something called the dummy variable trap, we have to drop one column of the dummy variable, meaning we will still have one column associated with the diagnosis column.

In our case, instead of using one-hot encoding, we will use the following code in order to get rid of our one categorical column:

In [ ]:
#change the diagnosis column to numerical values for better analysis, we can either do that or using one-hot encoding technique.
data['diagnosis'] = data['diagnosis'].map({'M':1, 'B':0})

Visualize the data¶

In the next part, we will use seaborn and matplotlib to plot the data and to visualize the data.¶

we will visualize the data using the following methods:¶

  1. Histogram
  2. Boxplot
  3. Scatterplot
  4. Correlation matrix using Heatmap
  5. Pairplot

The reasons we choose this kinds of graphs are:

  1. Histogram: it is a graph that shows the distribution of the data, that can help us to understand the data, and to see if there is any pattern in the data.

  2. Boxplot: boxplots are way of visualize the distribution of the data, and based on five features: minimum, 25th percentile, median, 75th percentile, and maximum. That way, we can see multiple things about the data, such as:

    1) outliers: the outliers are the data that are far from the mean, and they can be used to determine if the data is normally distributed. 2) compares multiple distributions: the data can be compared to see if there is any pattern in the data.

  3. Scatterplot: it is a graph that shows the relationship between two variables, and it can be used to determine if there is any relationship between the two variables. The advantage of this graph is that it is easy to understand the relationship between the two variables and to determine if there is any relationship between them, and if so what kind of relationship it is (linear, non-linear, etc).

  4. correlation matrix: due to the big amout of variables, it's difficult to see and understand the relationship between each variable, that's why we are using correlation matrix. The correlation matrix is a matrix that shows the relationship between each variable, and it can be used to determine if there is any relationship between the variables. The advantage of using correlation matrix is that it allows you to have greater understanding of the relationship between the variables.

  5. Pairplot: pairs plot is a matrix of scatterplots that lets you understand the pairwise relationship between different variables in a dataset. it can often be used to determine which type of regression model is best for a dataset.

Implementing Machine Learning Algorithms.¶

We are going to solve classification problem using the following algorithms:¶

  1. K-Nearest Neighbors
  2. Logistic Regression
  3. Random Forest
  4. Support Vector Machine
  5. Naive Bayes
  6. Xgboost
  7. Neural Network

I choose to implement this algorithm due to the following reasons:¶

  1. Our question is about classification, so we need to use classification algorithms. these algorithms are used to classify the data.
  2. the data is not linearly separable, so we need to use non-linear algorithms.

implemnting minmax scaler and standard scaler to normalize the data.¶

The main idea behind feature scaling is to make the data more similar. The most common techniques of feature scaling are Normalization and Standardization.¶

Variables that are measured at different scales do not contribute equally to the model fitting & model learned function and might end up creating a bias.¶
Thus, to deal with this potential problem feature-wise normalization such as MinMax Scaling and StandardScaler is usually used prior to model fitting.¶

There are many ways to normalize the data, two of the most common are MinMaxScaling and StandardScaler:¶

1) The main idea behind minmax scaler is to scale the data to a range between 0 and 1 in order to make the data easier to learn.
2) The main advantage of standard scaler is that it is robust to outliers.
When normalizing the data, we need to notice that we are normalizing the data after the train test split, becuase if not we will have a leak of information.¶
For example, it we are using minmax scaler before we split it into train and test data, we might use the min and max of our test to normalize our train data, and that will lead to a leak of information.¶
In [ ]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler #MinMaxScaler is a class that normalizes the data 
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler #StandardScaler is a class that standardizes the data 

x = data.drop('diagnosis', axis=1)
y = data['diagnosis']
#we are splitting the data into train and test data, we will use train data to train the model and test data to test the model. 
scaler = MinMaxScaler()

implementing KNN algorithm¶

Knn is a classification algorithm that is used to classify the data.¶

knn also known as k-nearest neighbors is a method of classification that make classificaton or prediction about the group of data that is near to the data point.¶

The knn algorithm uses the euclidean distance to find the nearest neighbors, the algorithm then calculates the distance between the data points and assigns the class of the closest data point.¶

The main idea behind the knn algorithm is to find the nearest neighbors of the data point, and then assign the class of the closest data point.¶

It's important to note that the knn can be easily overfitted. Due to someting called "curse of dimensionality", the knn can be easily overfitted. We can try to eliminate the curse of dimensionality by using the following methods:¶

  1. PCA
  2. Dimensionality reduction
  3. Feature selection
  4. Feature engineering

While the techniques above are good at eliminating overfitting, they are not perfect, and the value of k can also impact the model’s behavior and it's important to put that in mind.¶

Feature importance¶

Feature Importance refers to techniques that calculate a score for all the input features for a given model.¶

the scores simply represent the “importance” of each feature. A higher score means that the specific feature will have a larger effect on the model that is being used to predict a certain variable.¶

one of the many ways to check feature importance is to check to coeffiecients of the model.¶

For example, both linear and logistic regression algorithms have a coeffiecient that represents the weight of each feature. for each feature if an assigned coefficient is a large (negative or positive) number, it has some influence on the prediction. On the contrary, if the coefficient is zero, it doesn't have any impact on the prediction.

In [ ]:

Implementing Random Forest Algorithm¶

Randon Forest is a classification algorithm that uses the decision trees to classify the data.¶

Random Forest is a meta-algorithm that combines decision trees to create a strong classifier. Random forest, consists of a large number of individual decision trees that operate as an ensemble. Each individual tree in the random forest spits out a class prediction and the class with the most votes becomes our model's prediction

Implementing Feature Selection¶

Feature selection is a technique that is used to select the most important features from the data. Feature selection is the process of reducing the number of input variables when we are trying to predict a target variable. Feature selection is very importanat in the machine learning process and in implementing machine learning algorithms, since chooseing the right features is very important and effect the performance of the model. Irrelevant or partially relevant features can negatively impact model performance.

There are few main types of feature selection techniques:¶

(1) Forward selection (2) Backward selection (3) Random feature selection (4) Recursive feature elimination (5) Feature ranking (6) Feature subset selection.

in this case, we will use RFE algorithm using sklearn to select the most important features. RFE stands for Recursive Feature Elimination, and it is a feature selection technique that uses the recursion principle.

Our implementation of RFE will be using the RandomForestClassifier algorithm. We already used feature importance to check the importance of each feature, and we can see that many of the features have a low importance to the model. First, we can start by removing the features with a low importance. However, when removing one feature, all the other feature coeefficients will be changed, from this reason, we will using the recursive feature elimination algorithm.

In [ ]:

#implementing shap (SHapley Additive exPlanations) values to check the explanation of the model  
"""
SHAP is a method that is used to explain the model's predictions. 
In medical questions, we often want to know what is the effect of a single feature on the model's predictions, and not only the prediction of the whole dataset.
It's important to learn about the model's predictions, and to understand the effect of a single feature on the model's predictions, in order to make a better decision, especially in medical questions.
The calculation of SHAP values is based on the average of the marginal effects of each feature on the model's predictions.
"""

import shap


explainer = shap.TreeExplainer(rf_best)

#shap_values is a matrix that contains the shap values for each sample and each feature

"""

Support Vector Machines are supervised learning models for classification and regression problems.
They can solve linear and non-linear problems and work well for many practical problems.
The idea of this model is to find a hyperplane that separates the data into two classes,
and then to classify new data points based on the distance to the hyperplane. 
The goal of the line is to maximizing the margin between the points on either side of the so called decision line (the hyperplane) 
so that the points on the one side of the line are more likely to be classified as belonging to the positive class, and the points on the other side are more likely to be classified as belonging to the negative class.
"""

Implementing Neural Network Algorithm¶

Neural Networks are a type of artificial neural network, which is a type of artificial neural network that is based on the idea of a network of neurons.¶

The neurons are connected by a weight matrix, which is a matrix of weights that connect the neurons.

each neuron is connected to all the other neurons in the network, and the weights are updated based on the error of the output of the neuron.

each neuron has activation function, which is a function that maps the input to the output.

we are going to use Neural Network for classification problems, however today Neural Network is used for both classification and regression problems.

we will be using the Keras library to implement the Neural Network.

In [ ]:

summary¶

In this work, we have used the following libraries:¶

  1. pandas, which is a library for data manipulation and analysis.
  2. numpy, which is a library for scientific computing and high-level mathematical functions.
  3. matplotlib, which is a library for plotting graphs.
  4. seaborn, which is a library for statistical data visualization.
  5. sklearn, uses the machine learning algorithms to train and test the model.
  6. keras, which is a library for building deep learning models.
  7. tensorflow, deep learning library uses for building neural networks.

First, we uses the pandas library to read the data and store it in a dataframe, then we uses the info and describe functions to get some information about the data.

we learn and clean the data using descriptive statistics and visualizations (in this case, we use the seaborn and matplotlib library to plot the data).

We also uses preprocessing techniques such as scaling and normalization, we didnt need to use onehotencodeing because we didnt have any categorical variables (other then the target variable).

later on, we use the machine learning algorithms to train and test the model.

The machine learning algorithms are used to train the model to predict the output of the data, in this case, the output is the class of the breast cancer classification.

All the models we use were classification models, since our traget variable is binary, and this is a classification problem.

We implement the following machine learning algorithms:¶

  1. k-nearest neighbors (k-NN). this is a classification algorithm that uses the distance between the test data and the training data to predict the class of the test data.
  2. support vector machine (SVM). this is a classification algorithm that uses a linear decision boundary to predict the class of the test data.
  3. naive bayes classifier. this is a classification algorithm that uses a Gaussian distribution to predict the class of the test data.
  4. logistic regression. this is a classification algorithm that uses a logistic regression function to predict the class of the test data.
  5. neural network. this is a algorithm that uses a neural network to predict the class of the test data.
  6. random forest. this is a classification algorithm that uses a random forest to predict the class of the test data.
  7. xgb (Extreme Gradient Boosting). this is a classification algorithm that uses a gradient boosting algorithm to predict the class of the test data.

At the end of each algorithm, we plot the confusion matrix to evaluate the model.

By using the confusion matrix, we can see how well the model is performing.

Below you can see the results and scores of each algorithm.
